| 0 || 0 || 1 || 1 || 2 || \u22121 || {{#expr:0/1*100 round 2}}% || {{dts|format=dmy|1982|05|30}} || 30 May 1982\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|TUN}} || CAF || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 4 || 0 || +4 || {{#expr:1/1*100 round 2}}% || {{dts|format=dmy|1988|10|19}} || 19 October 1988\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|TUR}} || UEFA || 14 || 5 || 6 || 3 || 27 || 16 || +11 || {{#expr:5/14*100 round 2}}% || {{dts|format=dmy|1966|11|16}} || 23 March 2018\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|USA}} || CONCACAF || 10 || 6 || 2 || 2 || 22 || 14 || +8 || {{#expr:6/10*100 round 2}}% || {{dts|format=dmy|1924|06|14}} || 2 June 2018\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|URU}} || CONMEBOL || 4 || 1 || 1 || 2 || 6 || 7 || \u22121 || {{#expr:1/4*100 round 2}}% || {{dts|format=dmy|1974|05|08}} || 4 June 2017\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|WAL}} || UEFA || 17 || 6 || 4 || 7 || 18 || 18 || 0 || {{#expr:6/17*100 round 2}}% || {{dts|format=dmy|1960|09|28}} || 16 October 2018\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Total !! 78 nations !! 571 !! 225 !! 159 !! 187 !! 787 !! 700 !! +87 !!{{#expr:224/567*100 round 2}}% !! !!\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| colspan=\"12\" | a.{{Note|NoteA}}\"Germany\" includes nine games against [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] which were played between 1950 and German reunification in 1990.<br>b.{{Note|NoteB}}\"Serbia\" includes four games against Serbian predecessor (YUG/SFRY and FRY/SCG) teams.\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n[[File:Jack Charlton.jpg|thumb|175px|[[Jack Charlton]] is Ireland's most successful manager]]\n\n===Major===\n*'''[[FIFA World Cup]]'''\n:'''''Quarter finalists (1):''''' [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]]\n\n===Friendly titles===\n* '''[[Nations Cup (football)|Celtic Nations Cup]]'''\n:''''' Winners (1):''''' [[2011 Nations Cup|2011]]\n* '''[[Iceland Triangular Tournament]]'''\n:''''' Winners (1):''''' [[Iceland Triangular Tournament|1986]]\n\n===Other awards===\n* '''[[FIFA Fair Play Award]]'''\n:''''' Winners (1):''''' 1997\n* '''[[Unofficial Football World Championships]]'''\n:''''' Holders (2):''''' 30 March 1977 \u2013 1 July 1977, 31 March 2004 \u2013 29 May 2004\n\n==Recent results and forthcoming fixtures==\n{{See also|Republic of Ireland national football team 2010s results}}\n\nIreland began their qualification campaign for the [[UEFA Euro 2016]] tournament with a 2\u20131 away victory against Georgia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/qualifiers/season=2016/matches/round=2000446/match=2013814/postmatch/report/index.html |title=UEFA EURO 2016 \u2013 Matches |publisher=UEFA |accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> This was followed by a 7\u20130 home victory against Gibraltar,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/qualifiers/season=2016/matches/round=2000446/match=2013858/postmatch/report/index.html |title=UEFA EURO 2016 \u2013 Matches |publisher=UEFA |accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> and on 14 October 2014, the team played a 1\u20131 away draw against world champions, Germany, when a goal by [[John O'Shea]] won Ireland a late point in the 94th minute.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2014/1014/652368-germany-ireland/|title=O'Shea's 'fairytale ending' secures draw|publisher=RT\u00c9 Sport|date=14 October 2014}}</ref> They then suffered their first defeat of the campaign to Scotland; losing 1\u20130, before scoring another late goal through Shane Long to make it 1\u20131 and earn a well-deserved point against Poland at home. They then drew 1\u20131 at home to Scotland, before winning 3 games in a row against Gibraltar, Georgia and Germany; 4\u20130, 1\u20130 and 1\u20130 respectively. Shane Long scored the memorable winner against the World Champions Germany. However, in their last group game, they lost 2\u20131 away to Poland and missed out on an qualifying spot, finishing third in the group and advancing to the [[play-offs]]. They were drawn against [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]] in the play-offs. They drew the first leg away 1\u20131, and won the second leg 2\u20130, winning 3\u20131 on aggregate and qualifying for [[UEFA Euro 2016]] in France.\n\n===Schedule===\n{{updated|18 November 2019}}\n<small>Republic of Ireland goal tally first.</small><ref>{{cite web|title=Senior Men Matches|url=http://www.fai.ie/ireland/senior-men/matches |publisher=Football Association of Ireland|accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Competition\n! Venue\n! Opponent\n! Result\n! Scorers\n|-style=\"background:#ffc\"\n| 7 June 2019\n| UEFA Euro 2020 Qualification\n| Copenhagen, Denmark\n|align=left|{{fb|Denmark}}\n| 1\u20131\n|align=left |[[Pierre-Emile H\u00f8jbjerg]] {{goal|}}, [[Shane Duffy]] {{goal|85}}\n|-style=\"background:#cfc\"\n| 10 June 2019\n| UEFA Euro 2020 Qualification\n| Dublin, Ireland\n|align=left|{{fb|Gibraltar}}\n| 2\u20130\n|align=left |[[Joseph Chipolina]] {{goal|29|o.g.}}, [[Robbie Brady]] {{goal|90+3}}\n|-style=\"background:#ffc\"\n| 5 September 2019\n| UEFA Euro 2020 Qualification\n| Dublin, Ireland\n|align=left|{{fb|Switzerland}}\n| 1\u20131\n|align=left|[[Fabian Sch\u00e4r]] {{goal|74}}, [[David McGoldrick]] {{goal|85}}\n|-style=\"background:#cfc\"\n| 10 September 2019\n| Friendly match\n| Dublin, Ireland\n|align=left|{{fb|Bulgaria}}\n| 3\u20131\n|align=left |[[Alan Browne (footballer)|Alan Browne]] {{goal|56}}, [[Ivelin Popov]] {{goal|67|pen.}}, [[Kevin Long (footballer)|Kevin Long]] {{goal|83}}, [[James Collins (footballer, born 1990)|James Collins]] {{goal|86}}\n|-style=\"background:#ffc\"\n| 12 October 2019\n| UEFA Euro 2020 Qualification\n| Tbilisi, Georgia\n|align=left|{{fb|Georgia}}\n|0\u20130\n|\n|-style=\"background:#fbb\"\n| 15 October 2019\n| UEFA Euro 2020 Qualification\n| Geneva, Switzerland\n|align=left|{{fb|Switzerland}}\n|0\u20132\n|align=left |[[Haris Seferovi\u0107]] {{goal|16}}, [[Edimilson Fernandes]] {{goal|90+3}}\n|-style=\"background:#cfc\"\n| 1