 World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group C#Standings|4/6]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Russia}} [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group D|2018]]\n|12\n|5\n|5\n|2\n|13\n|11\n|2/6 Lost [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Second Round|Play-off]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Qatar}} [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]]\n|rowspan=2 colspan=8|''To be determined''\n|rowspan=2 colspan=7|''To be determined''\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Canada}} {{flagicon|Mexico}} {{flagicon|United States}} [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026]]\n|-\n!'''Total'''\n!'''Quarter-finals'''\n!'''3/21'''\n!'''13'''\n!'''2'''\n!'''8'''\n!'''3'''\n!'''10'''\n!'''10'''\n!'''141'''\n!'''56'''\n!'''43'''\n!'''42'''\n!'''199'''\n!'''169'''\n!\n|}\n\n:''Draws include knockout matches decided by [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]].''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align: center;font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!colspan=5|FIFA World Cup history\n|-\n!Year!!Round!!Score!!Result!!Republic of Ireland scorers\n|-\n|rowspan=5|[[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]]\n|Round 1||align=\"left\"|{{fb|IRL}} '''1 \u2013 1''' {{fb|ENG}}||Draw||[[Kevin Sheedy (Irish footballer)|Kevin Sheedy]] {{goal|73}}\n|-\n|Round 1||align=\"left\"|{{fb|IRL}} '''1 \u2013 1''' {{fb|NED}}||Draw||[[Niall Quinn]] {{goal|71}}\n|-\n|Round 1||align=\"left\"|{{fb|IRL}} '''0 \u2013 0''' {{fb|EGY}}||Draw||\n|-\n|Round 2||align=\"left\"|{{fb|IRL}} '''0(5) \u2013 0(4)''' {{fb|ROU}}||Draw||\n|-\n|Quarter-finals||align=\"left\"|{{fb|IRL}} '''0 \u2013 1''' {{fb|ITA}}||Loss||\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]]\n|Round 1||align=\"left\"|{{fb|IRL}} '''1 \u2013 0''' {{fb|ITA}}||Win||[[Ray Houghton]] {{goal|11}}\n|-\n|Round 1||align=\"left\"|{{fb|IRL}} '''1 \u2013 2''' {{fb|MEX}}||Loss||[[John Aldridge]] {{goal|84}}\n|-\n|Round 1||align=\"left\"|{{fb|IRL}} '''0 \u2013 0''' {{fb|NOR}}||Draw||\n|-\n|Round 2||align=\"left\"|{{fb|IRL}} '''0 \u2013 2''' {{fb|NED}}||Loss||\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002]]\n|Round 1||align=\"left\"|{{fb|IRL}} '''1 \u2013 1''' {{fb|CMR}}||Draw||[[Matt Holland]] {{goal|52}}\n|-\n|Round 1||align=\"left\"|{{fb|IRL}} '''1 \u2013 1''' {{fb|GER}}||Draw||[[Robbie Keane]] {{goal|90+2}}\n|-\n|Round 1||align=\"left\"|{{fb|IRL}} '''3 \u2013 0''' {{fb|KSA}}||Win||[[Robbie Keane]] {{goal|7}}<br>[[Gary Breen]] {{goal|61}}<br>[[Damien Duff]] {{goal|87}}\n|-\n|Round 2||align=\"left\"|{{fb|IRL}} '''1(2) \u2013 1(3)''' {{fb|ESP}}||Draw||[[Robbie Keane]] {{goal|90|pen.}}\n|}\n\n===UEFA European Championship===\n[[File:ITA-IRL 2016-06-22.svg|thumb|Irish line up for Ireland's fixture against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] at [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]]]]\n{{See also|Republic of Ireland at the UEFA European Championship}}\nIreland reached the quarter finals of the [[1964 European Nations Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccer-ireland.com/irish-qualifying-campaigns/nations-cup-1964.htm |title=Irish Football: Republic of Ireland 1964 European Nations Cup Qualifying Campaign: Iceland: Austria: Spain |website=Soccer-Ireland.com |accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIreland did not qualify for a European Championship until [[UEFA Euro 1988|Euro 1988]]. On 12 June 1988 in [[Stuttgart]], the Irish team took to the pitch in its first match at a major championship finals against England. Ray Houghton of [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] scored the only goal of the match as Ireland recorded a memorable and historic victory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1988/matches/round=212/match=13/postmatch/report/index.html|title=UEFA EURO 1988 \u2013 History \u2013 England-Republic of Ireland \u2013 UEFA|last=uefa.com|date=5 October 2003|publisher=UEFA|access-date=5 May 2017|language=en}}</ref> The game is fondly remembered in Irish folklore through the song \"Joxer goes to Stuttgart\" by Irish folk legend Christy Moore.<ref>{{cite web|last=TiocfaidhArLa1967|title=Christy Moore \u2013 Joxer Goes To Stuttgart|date=13 February 2010|website=YouTube|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5EPU65KCNug|accessdate=5 May 2017}}</ref> Ireland took on the former [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]] next and took the lead late in the first half via a spectacular volley from Liverpool's Ronnie Whelan. Unfortunately for both Whelan and Ireland the lead was cancelled out midway through the second half by Oleh Protasov as the match ended in a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccer-ireland.com/euro-1988/index.htm |title=Republic of Ireland: Euro 1988 Finals: West Germany: England: Soviet Union: Holland |website=Soccer-Ireland.com |accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> In their final match, Ireland lost out to the Netherlands 1\u20130.\n\nIt was not until 2011 that Ireland clinched a place at another European Championship, qualifying for [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]] with a 5\u20131 aggregate victory over [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccer-ireland.com/irish-qualifying-campaigns/euro-2012.htm |title=Irish Football: Republic of Ireland Euro 2012 Soccer Fixtures & Qualifying Campaign: Group B Qualifiers: Russia: Slovakia: FYR Macedonia: Armenia: Andorra |website=Soccer-Ireland.com |accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> At the tournament itself, however, Ireland lost all three of its matches and conceded nine goals, the nation's worst performance in a major tournament to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccer-ireland.com/euro-2012/index.htm |title=Republic of Ireland: Euro 2012 Finals: Spain: Italy: Croatia: Poland |website=Soccer-Ireland.com |date=2 December 2011 |accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIreland qualified to [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]] following a play-off victory over [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=2295515.html |author=uefa.com |title=Walters double takes Ireland to UEFA EURO 2016 |date=16 November 2015 |accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref> In the group stages they drew 1\u20131 with [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]], having initially taken the lead through a [[Wes Hoolahan]] strike, before being beaten 3\u20130 by [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] in the following game. However, a 1\u20130 victory over [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in their final game, courtesy of a late header from [[Robbie Brady]], earned the side a spot in the round of 16, the first time the team had ever advanced from the group stage at a European Championship. In the round of 16, Ireland faced the hosts [[France national football team|France]] and, after taking an early lead through a Brady penalty, were beaten 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2016/teams/team=64/matches/index.html |author=uefa.com |title=UEFA EURO 2016 \u2013 History \u2013 Republic of Ireland|date=15 June 2017 |accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"9\" |[[Republic of Ireland at the UEFA European Championship|Championship record]]\n! rowspan=\"20\" style=\"width:1%;\"|\n! colspan=\"7\" |[[UEFA European Championship qualifying]] record\n|-\n!Year\n!Round\n!Position\n!{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!Position\n|-\n|{{flagicon|France}} [[1960 European Nations' Cup#Qualifying|1960]]\n| colspan=8 rowspan=7 |''Did not qualify''\n|2\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|2\n|4\n|Preliminary round\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Spain|1945}} [[1964 European Nations' Cup qualifying#Quarter-finals|1964]]\n|6\n|2\n|2\n|2\n|9\n|12\n|Quarter-finals\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Italy|1946}} [[UEFA Euro 1968 qualifying#Group 1|1968]]\n|6\n|2\n|1\n|3\n|5\n|8\n|3/4\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Belgium}} [[UEFA Euro 1972 qualifying#Group 6|1972]]\n|6\n|0\n|1\n|5\n|3\n|17\n|4/4\n|-\n|{{flagic