 Everything|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806145512/http://nintendoeverything.com/top-100-best-selling-games-in-japan-during-the-first-half-of-2015/|archivedate=2015-08-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/nintendo-switch-ships-274m-units-zelda-rises-to-38/1100-6449626/|title=Nintendo Switch Ships 2.74M Units, Zelda Rises To 3.84M Shipped|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|date=27 April 2017|website=Gamespot.com|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Xeno2JPsales\">{{cite web|url=https://gematsu.com/2017/12/media-create-sales-11-27-17-12-3-17|title=Media Create Sales: 11/27/17 \u2013 12/3/17|last=Romano|first=Sal|date=6 December 2017|publisher=Gematsu|accessdate=6 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206201442/https://gematsu.com/2017/12/media-create-sales-11-27-17-12-3-17|archive-date=6 December 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2019/190425_3e.pdf |title=Earnings Release for Fiscal Year Ended March 2019 - Supplementary Information |date=March 31, 2019 |accessdate=April 25, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" | {{nihongo foot|''Kirby''|\u661f\u306e\u30ab\u30fc\u30d3\u30a3|Hoshi no K\u0101bi|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a series of [[action-platformer]] video games developed by [[HAL Laboratory]] and published by Nintendo. The series centers around the adventures of a young, pink alien hero named [[Kirby (character)|Kirby]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Fallout (series)|Fallout]]'' || [[1997 in video games|September 30, 1997]] || 38 million<ref>\n*[https://rpgcodex.net/content.php?id=10604 RPG Codex Report: A Codexian Visit to inXile Entertainment]: \"'''Brian Fargo:''' 400,000 sounds about right. I remember ''Fallout 1'' sold 600,000 units, and ''Planescape'' sold less than that. ''Baldur\u2019s Gate 1'' was our big seller. That was over a million copies.\" [April 2017]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20010203124200/http://desslock.gamespot.com/archives/200005/20000511.html Desslock's Ramblings \u2013 RPG Sales Figures]: \"''Fallout'' and ''Fallout 2'', which are considered to be two of the best RPGs released in recent years, sold approximately 144,000 and 123,000 copies, respectively, in PC Data's tracked data. Very good sales, especially since the overall figures are likely double those amounts, but considerably below the sales volumes for true blockbuster titles.\" [May 2000]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080723113339/http://www.acmi.net.au/global/docs/games_timeline_australia.pdf Timeline of Game Development in Australia]: \"Micro Fort\u00e9 releases Fallout Tactics, the next release in Interplay\u2019s fallout franchise, which sells over 300,000 units and goes to No. 2 in the US sales charts.\" [January 2008]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151113201845/http://www.polygon.com/2015/11/10/9673936/elder-scrolls-bigger-than-fallout-sales-data-report Fallout 4 could be a bigger hit than Skyrim]:  \"''Fallout 3'' (2008) surpassed ''Oblivion'', selling 12.4 million copies. ''Fallout: New Vegas'' (2010) \u2014 the only game on this list not actually developed by Bethesda Game Studios \u2014 performed just slightly lower, selling 11.6 million copies from its 2010 release date to now [November 2015].\" \n*[https://www.gamespot.com/articles/fallout-4-surpasses-skyrim-to-become-bethesdas-mos/1100-6447621/ Fallout 4 Surpasses Skyrim To Become Bethesda's Most Successful Game Ever]: \"Fallout 4, which came out in November 2015, shipped 12 million copies on launch day, though Bethesda has not provided a hard sales figure for the game since.\"\n*[https://www.superdataresearch.com/us-digital-games-market/ Worldwide digital games market: November 2018]: \"'''Battlefield V and Fallout 76 launches fail to meet franchise benchmarks.''' We estimate ''Battlefield V'' and ''Fallout 76'' sold 1.9 million and 1.4 million digital units, respectively, across console and PC at launch. Both are down from ''Battlefield 1'' and ''Fallout 4.''\"</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| ''Fallout'' is a series of [[post-apocalyptic]] role-playing video games. It was created by [[Interplay Entertainment]] and later developed by [[Bethesda Game Studios]] and [[Obsidian Entertainment]], and published by [[Bethesda Softworks]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|''[[Diablo (series)|Diablo]]'' || [[1996 in video games|December 31, 1996]] || 36.5 million<ref name=\"blizzarde32009\">{{cite web|author=Brendan Sinclair |title=Starcraft II by end of 2009, Call of Duty expanding to new genres |url=http://e3.gamespot.com/story/6210427/starcraft-ii-by-end-of-2009-call-of-duty-expanding-to-new-genres |website=[[GameSpot]] |date=2009-05-31 |accessdate=2009-06-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090602141340/http://e3.gamespot.com/story/6210427/starcraft-ii-by-end-of-2009-call-of-duty-expanding-to-new-genres |archivedate=2009-06-02 }}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" | ''Diablo'' is an action role-playing [[hack and slash]] [[dungeon crawler]] video game series developed by [[Blizzard North]] and published and later developed by [[Blizzard Entertainment]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\" |\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|''[[NBA Live (video game series)|NBA Live]]'' || [[1994 in video games|October 1994]] || 35 million<ref name=\"nba\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ea.com/news/dwight-howard-cover-athlete-nba-live-10 | publisher=[[Electronic Arts]]  | title=Dwight Howard Named Cover Athlete of EA SPORTS NBA LIVE 10 | date=2009-06-11 | accessdate=2009-08-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" | ''NBA Live'' is a series of [[basketball]] video games developed and published by [[EA Sports]] annually since 1995.\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\" |\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|''[[Mega Man]]''|| [[1987 in video games|December 17, 1987]] || 35{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"capcomseries\" />\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" |''Mega Man'', known as {{nihongo foot|''Rockman''|\u30ed\u30c3\u30af\u30de\u30f3|Rokkuman|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} in Japan, is a series of video games created by [[Capcom]], starring a series of characters each known by the moniker \"[[Mega Man (character)|Mega Man]]\".\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Animal Crossing]]'' || [[2001 in video games|April 14, 2001]] || 33.7 million<ref name=\"3ds\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/sales/software/3ds.html|title=IR Information : Sales Data - Top Selling Software Sales Units - Nintendo 3DS Software|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"nintendo.co.jp\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendofeed.com/2013/06/feature-is-animal-crossing-one-of.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20141104202710/http://www.nintendofeed.com/2013/06/feature-is-animal-crossing-one-of.html |archivedate=2014-11-04 }}</ref><ref name=\"MagicBoxUS\"/><ref name=081031e>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2009/090508e.pdf#page=6|title=Financial Results Briefing for the Fiscal Year Ended March 2009: Supplementary Information|accessdate=May 8, 2009|date=May 8, 2009|work=Financial Results Briefing for the 69th Fiscal Term Ended March 2009|publisher=Nintendo|pages=6|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629121637/http://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2009/090508e.pdf#page=6|archive-date=June 29, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2016/160427_4e.pdf |title=Supplementary Information about Earnings Release |date=April 27, 2016 |publisher=Nintendo |page=4 |accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.4gamer.net/games/117/G011794/20151202067/ |title=\u300c\u30e2\u30f3\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30cf\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30af\u30ed\u30b9\u