ign:center;\"\n| ''[[Cooking Mama]]'' ||March 23, 2006||12 million<ref name=\"cookingmama\">{{cite web | url=http://www.joystiq.com/2011/06/09/mama-franchise-reaches-12-million-sales-worldwide-8-5-million/ | title='Mama' franchise reaches 12 million sales worldwide, 8.5 million in NA |last=Sliwinski |first=Alexander | date=2011-06-09 | publisher=Joystiq | accessdate=2011-06-09}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| {{nihongo foot|''Cooking Mama''|\u30af\u30c3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 \u30de\u30de|Kukkingu Mama|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a series of [[cookery]] [[simulation game|simulation]]-styled [[minigame]] compilation [[video game]]s developed by [[Cooking Mama Limited]] (formerly known as Office Create) and published by [[Taito Corporation|Taito]] in Japan and for the [[iPhone]] OS, [[Majesco Entertainment]] in North America and [[505 Games]] in Europe.\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Europa Universalis]]'' ||October 20, 2000||12 million{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| Europa Universalis is a grand strategy game franchise that started in 2000 and has been one of paradox's leading franchises.\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[SOCOM (series)|SOCOM]]'' || August 27, 2002 || 12 million<ref name=\"socom\">{{cite web | publisher=[[1Up.com]] | date=2010-03-04 | accessdate=2010-03-07 | url=http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3178223 | title=Sony Announces SOCOM 4}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| ''SOCOM'' is a series of [[third-person shooter]] video games created by [[Zipper Interactive]]. The games focus on various teams of [[United States Navy SEALs]] completing missions with occasional help from other special operations forces from around the world such as the [[Special Air Service|SAS]], [[Special Boat Service|SBS]], and [[GROM]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Star Fox (series)|Star Fox]]'' || [[1993 in video gaming|February 21, 1993]] || 12 million<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/500185?view=credit |title=BFI &#124; Film & TV Database &#124; VIDEO GAMES (1993) |publisher=Ftvdb.bfi.org.uk |date=2009-04-16 |accessdate=2012-08-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018105920/http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/500185?view=credit |archive-date=2012-10-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| {{nihongo foot|''Star Fox''|\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30d5\u30a9\u30c3\u30af\u30b9|Sut\u0101Fokkusu|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[video game]] series created by [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] from [[Nintendo]] during the early 1990s. The original game was a forward-scrolling 3D [[Sci-Fi]] [[Shoot 'em up#Tube and rail shooters|rail shooter]]. Later sequels added more directional freedom as the series progressed. The game concept was inspired by a shrine to a fox god who could fly, which [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] visited regularly. The shrine was accessible through a series of arches, thus, inspiring the gameplay.<ref>''Equinox - Serious Fun'' (AKA 'Video Games') (1993) Channel 4.</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[List of Galaxian video games|Galaxian]]'' || [[1979 in video gaming|October 1979]] || 12 million{{#tag:ref|''Galaxian'' series:\n* ''Galaxian3'' sales: 66,770 units (JP)<ref name=\"Game Search\"/>\n* ''SD Gundam: Over Galaxian'' sales: 27,905 (JP)<ref name=\"Game Search\"/>\n* ''Namco Museum Vol. 1'' sales: 1.65 million units (US),<ref name=\"MagicBoxUS\">{{cite web |title=US Platinum Videogame Chart |url=http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-USPlatinum.shtml |website=The Magic Box |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref> 167,786 units (JP)<ref name=\"Game Search\">{{cite web |title=Game Search (based on Famitsu data) |url=https://sites.google.com/site/gamedatalibrary/game-search |website=Game Data Library |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424035430/https://sites.google.com/site/gamedatalibrary/game-search |archivedate=24 April 2019 |date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Namco Museum Vol. 3'' sales: 2.24 million units (US),<ref name=\"MagicBoxUS\"/> 148,758 units (JP)<ref name=\"Game Search\"/>\n* ''Namco Museum 64'' sales: 1.04 million units<ref name=\"MagicBoxUS\"/>\n* ''Namco Museum'' (GBA) sales: 2.96 million units<ref name=\"MagicBoxUS\"/>\n* ''Namco Museum'' (PS2) sales: \u22481.80 million units<ref name=\"MagicBoxUS\"/>\n* ''Namco Museum Battle Collection'' sales: 79,527 units (JP)<ref name=\"Game Search\"/>\n* ''Namco Museum Vol. 2'' (PSP) sales: 24,934 units (JP)<ref name=\"Game Search\"/>\n* ''Namco Museum DS'' sales: 33,393 units (JP)<ref name=\"Game Search\"/>\n* ''Namco Museum Virtual Arcade'' sales: 5,912 units (JP)<ref name=\"Game Search\"/>\n* ''Namco Arcade'' downloads: 2 million<ref>{{cite web |title=Namco Arcade |url=https://toucharcade.com/games/namco-arcade |website=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=1 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806211940/https://toucharcade.com/games/namco-arcade |archivedate=6 August 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Pac-Man & Galaga Dimensions'' sales: 10,785 units (JP)<ref name=\"Game Search\"/>\n|group=n|name=Galaxian}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| {{nihongo foot|''Galaxian''|\u30ae\u30e3\u30e9\u30af\u30b7\u30a2\u30f3|Gyarakushian|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a series of fixed shooter video games developed by [[Namco]], now known as [[Bandai Namco Entertainment]]. Beginning in arcades in 1979 with ''[[Galaxian]]'', it has seen multiple sequels, spin-offs, and re-imaginings, as well as dozens of ports and inclusions in Namco game compilations. ''Galaxian'' and its sequel ''[[Galaga]]'' are listed among the most recognizable and popular games during the [[golden age of arcade video games]], and are cited as being important and influential for the shoot'em up genre and industry as a whole.\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Momotaro Dentetsu]]'' || October 26, 1987 || 12 million<ref>{{cite news |title=\"\u6843\u9244\"\u521d\u3002iPhone/iPod touch\u7528\u30dc\u30fc\u30c9\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u300c\u6843\u592a\u90ce\u96fb\u9244JAPAN\uff0b\uff08\u30d7\u30e9\u30b9\uff09\u300d\u304c\u672c\u65e5\u914d\u4fe1\u958b\u59cb\u3002\u6b63\u5348\u304b\u3089\u306fUstream\uff06\u30c4\u30a4\u30ad\u30e3\u30b9\u3067\u306eWeb\u767a\u8868\u4f1a\u3082 |url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/128/G012883/20110217003/ |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=[[4Gamer.net]] |date=2011-02-17 |language=ja}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| {{nihongo foot|''Momotaro Dentetsu''|\u6843\u592a\u90ce\u96fb\u9244|Momotar\u014d Dentetsu|[[Momotar\u014d]] Electric Railway|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} (also known by the abbreviated name ''Momotetsu'') is a long-running [[board game]]-style video game series in Japan. The game mechanics are often compared to the board games [[sugoroku]] and [[Monopoly (game)|Monopoly]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Jak and Daxter]]'' || December 4, 2001 || 12 million<ref name=jak>{{cite web|title=Naughty Dog - 30 Year Timeline|url=http://www.naughtydog.com/timeline/|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|accessdate=11 January 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150813121753/http://www.naughtydog.com/timeline/|archivedate=13 August 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" | ''Jak and Daxter'' is a series of [[open world]] [[3D computer graphics|3D]] [[platform game|platform]]/[[shooter game|shooter]]/[[racing game|racing]] [[video game]]s. Originally developed by [[Naughty Dog]] and published by [[Sony Computer Entertainment]] for the [[PlayStation 2]], the franchise has appeared on the [[PlayStation Portable]], [[PlayStation Vita]], [[PlayStation 3]], and [[PlayStation 4]] video game systems.\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"backgroun