 strategy game|strategic]], [[maze]]-based [[computer]] and video game franchise originally developed and published by [[Hudson Soft]] and is currently owned by [[Konami]]. The original game was published in [[1983 in video gaming|1983]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Nobunaga's Ambition]]'' || [[1983 in video gaming|1983]] || 10 million<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gematsu.com/2018/03/nobunagas-ambition-series-tops-10-million-shipments|title=Nobunaga's Ambition series tops 10 million shipments|date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| {{nihongo foot|''Nobunaga's Ambition''|\u4fe1\u9577\u306e\u91ce\u671b|Nobunaga no Yab\u014d|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a turn-based [[Wargame (video games)|computerized wargame]] series by [[Koei]] that originated from Japan. The games are set during the [[Sengoku period]] of [[feudal Japan]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Taiko no Tatsujin]]'' || [[2001 in video gaming|February 21, 2001]] || 10 million<ref>{{cite web |last1=Romano |first1=Sal |title=Taiko no Tatsujin console game sales top 10 million, Drum 'n' Fun adds new versus mode |url=https://gematsu.com/2019/05/taiko-no-tatsujin-console-game-sales-top-10-million-drum-n-fun-adds-new-versus-mode |website=Gematsu |accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| {{nihongo foot|''Taiko no Tatsujin''|\u592a\u9f13\u306e\u9054\u4eba|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a series of rhythm video games developed and published by [[Bandai Namco Entertainment]], beginning in 2001 with the arcade game ''Taiko no Tatsujin''. The player uses a taiko drum to play alongside the music, using two large sticks known as \"bachi\" to hit it. Several releases of the series were made for arcades, home game consoles, handheld systems and mobile phones, the latest being the Nintendo Switch title ''[[Taiko no Tatsujin: Drum 'n' Fun!]]'', releases in 2018.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Buzz!]]'' ||October 21, 2005|| 10 million<ref>{{cite web|last1=Phillips|first1=Tom|title=Buzz! developer Relentless shut down|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-08-05-buzz-developer-relentless-shut-down|website=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|accessdate=7 August 2016|date=5 August 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| ''Buzz!'' is a series of video games originated by Sleepydog Ltd., developed by [[Relentless Software]] and published by [[Sony Computer Entertainment]] Europe for the [[PlayStation 2]] console. They are [[quiz]] games that sees the players answering trivia questions whilst competing in the fictional game show, Buzz.\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Colin McRae Rally]]'' || July 1998 || 10 million<ref name=\"colinrally\">{{cite news | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article2469101.ece | newspaper=The Times | date=2007-09-17 | accessdate=2009-03-21 | title=Colin McRae | location=London | first=Anushka | last=Asthana}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| ''Colin McRae Rally'' is a [[racing]] video game series developed and published by [[Codemasters]]. The series is named after the late [[World Rally Championship]] driver [[Colin McRae]], who provided technical advice during development.\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Deer Hunter (series)|Deer Hunter]]'' || December 31, 1997 || 10 million<ref name=\"deerhunter\">{{cite web | url=http://archive.gamespy.com/devcorner/february02/witchboyhk/index2.shtm | work=Witchboy Goes to Honk Kong | accessdate=2009-03-21 | author=Harvey Smith | title=Day Two | publisher=[[GameSpy]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| ''Deer Hunter'' is a first-person shooting game series of North American video games published by [[WizardWorks]], a division of [[Infogrames]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'' || October 21, 2002|| 10 million<ref name=\"lotr\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/2049/gdc_2004_game_design_keynote_the_.php | title=GDC 2004 Game Design Keynote: The Making of The Return of the King | work=Postcard From GDC 2004 | publisher=[[Gamasutra]] | accessdate=2009-03-21 | date=2004-03-24 | author=Brad Kane}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| Based on the series of movies ''The Lord of the Rings'' by [[Peter Jackson]], the series include ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Two Towers (video game)|The Lord of the Rings: The Two Towers]]'' and ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King (video game)|The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]'', published by Electronic Arts.\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Pitfall!]]'' || April 20, 1982 || 10 million<ref name=\"pitfall\">{{cite press release | url=http://investor.activision.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=309754 | publisher=[[Activision]] | date=2008-05-12 | accessdate=2009-03-21 | title=Activision Swings into Action with \"Pitfall: The Big Adventure\" For Wii}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| ''Pitfall!'' is a series of [[platform game]]s developed by [[Activision]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[The Settlers]]'' || June 30, 1993 || 10 million<ref name=\"ubisoftgroup\"/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"| ''The Settlers''{{efn|{{lang-de|Die Siedler}}}} (also known as ''Serf City'') is a slow-paced [[real time strategy]] [[video game]] by German developer [[Blue Byte]].\n|}\n\n== At least 5 million copies ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:33.4%;\"| [[list of video game franchises|Franchise name]]\n! style=\"width:33.3%;\"| Original release date\n! styl