ative]] and competitive gameplay.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Ninja Gaiden]]'' || [[1988 in video gaming|December 9, 1988]] || 7.705 million{{#tag:ref|''Ninja Gaiden'' series:\n* Series sales as of June 2007: 5.5 million<ref name=\"tecmofranchises\">{{cite web | url=http://www.tecmo.co.jp/company/data/20070823cp_e.pdf#page=13 | title=TECMO Corporate Profile (as of June 2007) | page=12 | format=PDF | accessdate=2008-01-07 | publisher=[[Tecmo]] | date=August 23, 2007}}</ref>\n* Sales from June 2007 to December 2008: 2.205 million<ref>{{cite web|title=Financial Statements Summary for Fiscal Year Ended December 2008|url=http://www.tecmo.co.jp/company/data/20090216gaikyo_e.pdf#page=5|publisher=[[Tecmo]]|accessdate=22 April 2012|page=4|date=February 16, 2009}}</ref>\n|name=NinjaGaiden|group=n}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| {{nihongo foot|''Ninja Gaiden''|\u5fcd\u8005\u5916\u4f1d|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a series of video games by [[Tecmo]] featuring the [[dragon]] [[ninja]], [[Ryu Hayabusa]]. The series was originally known as {{nihongo foot|''Ninja Ryukenden''|\u5fcd\u8005\u9f8d\u5263\u4f1d|Ninja Ry\u016bkenden|lit. \"Legend of the Ninja Dragon Sword\"|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} in Japan, while the original arcade title and early home installments of the series were usually known as ''Shadow Warriors'' in the [[PAL region]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Romance of the Three Kingdoms (video game series)|Romance of the Three Kingdoms]]'' || [[1985 in video gaming|10 December 1985]] || 7.5 million<ref name=\"rottk\">[https://www.koeitecmo.co.jp/news/2016/09/11-1.html] Koei Tecmo</ref><ref>https://shop.gamecity.ne.jp/goods/305405313600310001.htm</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| {{nihongo foot|''Romance of the Three Kingdoms''|\u4e09\u570b\u5fd7|Sangokushi|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a turn-based [[Wargame (video games)|computerized wargame]] series by [[Koei]] that originated from Japan. The games cover events of the ''[[Romance of the Three Kingdoms]]'' and the ''[[Sanguo Zhi|Chronicles of the Three Kingdoms]]'' in China during the 2nd and 3rd centuries.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Max Payne (series)|Max Payne]]'' || [[2001 in video gaming|July 25, 2001]] || 7.5 million<ref name=\"gta\" />\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''Max Payne'' is a [[third-person shooter]] video game series originally developed by the Finnish company [[Remedy Entertainment]], produced by [[3D Realms]] and published by [[Gathering of Developers]]. Later versions were published and developed by [[Rockstar Games]]. The ''Max Payne'' series has a major cinematic influence: the [[Hong Kong]] action movie genre, particularly the work of director [[John Woo]], which features a great deal of slow-motion violence and gunfights, almost resembling [[ballet]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Ace Attorney]]'' || [[2001 in video gaming|October 11, 2001]] || 7.3 million<ref name=\"capcomseries\"/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''Ace Attorney'', known as {{nihongo foot|''Turnabout Trial''|\u9006\u8ee2\u88c1\u5224|''Gyakuten Saiban''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} in Japan, is an adventure visual novel-style game series, by creator [[Shu Takumi]]. It is owned,  developed and published by [[Capcom]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[King's Quest]]'' || [[1980 in video gaming|1980]] || 7 million<ref>{{cite web |title=King's Quest: Collection Series (1997) DOS box cover art |url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/kings-quest-collection-series/cover-art/gameCoverId,84305/ |website=[[MobyGames]] |publisher=Blue Flame Labs |accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''King's Quest'' is a [[graphic adventure game]] series created by the American software company [[Sierra Entertainment]]. It is widely considered a classic series from the golden era of adventure games. Following the success of its first installments, the series was primarily responsible for building the reputation of Sierra. [[Roberta Williams]], co-founder and former co-owner of Sierra, designed all of the ''King's Quest'' games until the series' [[King's Quest (2015 video game)|reboot in 2015]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Samurai Warriors]]'' || [[2004 in video gaming|February 11, 2004]] || 7 million<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180106173331/http://www.gifu-np.co.jp/news/kennai/20160903/201609030904_27966.shtml] Gifu News</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| {{nihongo foot|''Samurai Warriors''|\u6226\u56fd\u7121\u53cc|Sengoku Mus\u014d|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a series of [[hack and slash]] video games created by [[Koei]]. The franchise is set during the [[Sengoku period]] of Japanese history and has similar system of [[Dynasty Warriors]] series.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Moto Racer]]'' || [[1997 in video gaming|August 31, 1997]] || 7 million<ref name=\"motoracer\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/moto-racer-ds-multi-discipline-motorbike-title-heading-for-ds | title=Moto Racer DS | accessdate=2009-03-21 | date=2008-05-23 | publisher=Nobilis Publishing}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''Moto Racer'' is a sports video game franchise based on motorbikes developed and published by Nobilis.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Oddworld]]'' || [[1997 in video gaming|September 19, 1997]] || 7 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-03-18-New-n-Tasty-needs-to-sell-500K-to-fund-an-original-new-Oddworld-game|title=New 'n' Tasty needs to sell 500K to fund an ori