ess World Records]] as the best-selling first-person shooter game series. It is also the most successful video game franchise created in the [[United States]] and is the best-selling video game franchise not owned by Nintendo. In addition to main series sales, there have been over 100 million downloads of the mobile spin-off, ''[[Call of Duty: Mobile]]''.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\" |\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|''[[Grand Theft Auto]]''||[[1997 in video games|October 21, 1997]]|| 300 million<ref>{{cite web|title=''Grand Theft Auto'' life-time sales hit 250 million, GTA 5 and GTA Online ships 70 million units|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/grand-theft-auto-life-time-sales-hits-250-million-gta-5-gta-online-ships-70-million-units-1589687|website=www.ibtimes.co.uk|date=3 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"variety.com\">{{cite web|title=More Than 100 Million Copies of 'GTA V' Sold, 'GTA Online' Continues to Thrive|url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/gta-v-100-million-sales-1203022310/|website=[[variety (magazine)|variety]]|date=8 November 2018|access-date=17 November 2018}}.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gameblog.fr/news/88504-gta-v-a-120-millions-red-dead-2-pres-des-30-millions-rocksta|title=GTA V \u00e0 120 millions, Red Dead 2 pr\u00e8s des 30 millions : Rockstar publie ses bons chiffres de ventes|date=7 February 2020|last=Pillon|first=Thomas|lang=fr|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208050531/http://www.gameblog.fr/news/88504-gta-v-a-120-millions-red-dead-2-pres-des-30-millions-rocksta|archive-date=8 February 2020|access-date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" |''Grand Theft Auto'' is an [[open world]] [[Action-adventure game|action-adventure]] video game series created by [[David Jones (video game developer)|David Jones]] and [[Mike Dailly (game designer)|Mike Dailly]]; the later titles of which were created by brothers [[Dan Houser|Dan]] and [[Sam Houser]], [[Leslie Benzies]] and Aaron Garbut. It is primarily developed by Scottish developer [[Rockstar North]] and published by [[Rockstar Games]], and includes ten stand-alone games and multiple expansion packs. It is the most successful video game franchise originating from the [[United Kingdom]] and is the best-selling action-adventure and open world series'.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|''[[FIFA (video game series)|FIFA]]'' || [[1993 in video games|Christmas 1993]] || 260 million<ref name=\"fifa\">{{cite news |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-09-05-fifa-18-sells-over-24-million-copies |title=FIFA 18 sells over 24 million copies |last=Vincent |first=James |website=[[Gamesindustry.biz]] |date=September 5, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''FIFA'' is a series of [[association football]] based sports games, released yearly by [[Electronic Arts]] under the [[EA Sports]] brand. It is the first to have an official license from the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] (International Federation of Association Football), the international governing body of football.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Wii (video game series)|Wii]]'' || [[2006 in video games|November 19, 2006]] || 202.57 million{{#tag:ref|''Wii Series'':\n* ''[[Wii Sports]]'': 82.86 million<ref name=\"nintendotop_wii\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/sales/software/wii.html|title=Nintendo Top Selling Software Sales Units: Wii|date=2012-03-31|accessdate=2016-05-12|publisher=[[Nintendo]]}}</ref>\n* ''[[Wii Sports Resort]]'': 33.09 million<ref name=\"nintendotop_wii\"/>\n* ''[[Wii Play]]'': 28.02 million<ref name=\"nintendotop_wii\"/>\n* ''[[Wii Fit]]'': 22.67 million<ref name=\"nintendotop_wii\"/>\n* ''[[Wii Fit Plus]]'': 21.13 million<ref name=\"nintendotop_wii\"/>\n* ''[[Wii Party]]'': 9.32 million<ref name=\"nintendotop_wii\"/>\n* ''[[Wii Music]]'': 2.65 million<ref name=\"nintendo_m09\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2009/090508e.pdf#page=6|title=Financial Results Briefing for the Fiscal Year Ended March 2009: Supplementary Information|accessdate=2009-05-08|date=2009-05-08|work=Financial Results Briefing for the 69th Fiscal Term Ended March 2009|publisher=Nintendo|page=6}}</ref>\n* ''[[Wii Party U]]'': 1.58{{nbsp}}million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/sales/software/wiiu.html |title=Top Selling Software Sales Units |website=Nintendo |date=September 30, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151028233935/http://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/sales/software/wiiu.html |archivedate=2015-10-28 |url-status=dead |accessdate=November 18, 2015}}</ref>\n* ''[[Wii Play: Motion]]'': 1.26 million<ref name=\"nintendo_mar12\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2012/120427e.pdf#page=7|title=Financial Results Briefing for the Fiscal Year Ended March 2012|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|date=2012-04-27|format=PDF|accessdate=2012-05-14|page=6}}</ref>\n|group=n|name=Wii}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | The ''Wii'' series of [[simulation video game]]s was created for Nintendo by Shigeru Miyamoto in 2006. The first game in the series, ''[[Wii Sports]]'', was bundled with the original [[Wii]] console and is one the best-selling games of all time.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[List of Tetris variants|Tetris]]'' || [[1988 in video games|January 29, 1988]]{{efn|The release date of the first ''Tetris'' games sold commercially.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/29/business/new-software-game-it-comes-from-soviet.html|title=New Software Game: It Comes From Soviet|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=1988-01-29}}</ref> Earlier games were given out for free.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vadim.oversigma.com/Tetris.htm|title=Tetris Story|last=Gerasimov|first=Vadim|accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref>}} || 202 million{{efn|''Tetris'' sold 70{{nbsp}}million physical retail units<ref name=guardian020609>''[[The Guardian]]'', June 2, 2009, [https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/jun/02/tetris-25anniversary-alexey-pajitnov How Tetris conquered the world, block by block] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329135242/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/jun/02/tetris-25anniversary-alexey-pajitnov |date=March 29, 2015 }}</ref> and 132{{nbsp}}million paid [[mobile game]] downloads.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tetris\u00ae Franchise and Licensing Works!\u00ae Launch Dozens of New Merchandise Categories at Las Vegas Licensing International Expo |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110614005792/en/Tetris%C2%AE-Franchise-Licensing-Works%21%C2%AE-Launch-Dozens-New |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=June 14, 2011 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | ''[[Tetris]]'' is a falling-blocks [[puzzle video game]], created by [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] game designer [[Alexey Pajitnov]] in [[1984 in video games|1984]]. It was later commercialized and released on a vast spectrum of platforms, from [[video game console]]s and [[PC game|computers]] to [[mobile device]]s and calculators, with the version bundled with the [[Game Boy]] selling over 35 million units.<ref name=\"tetris\">{{cite news | url=https://venturebeat.com/2014/04/07/mr-tetris-explains-why-the-puzzle-game-is-still-popular-after-three-decades-interview/| title='Mr. Tetris' explains why the puzzle game is still popular after three decades (interview)| work=VentureBeat | date=2014-04-07| accessdate=2016-05-12|first=Dean|last=Takahashi}}</ref> It is the most successful video game franchise to originate from [[Russia]] and the former [[Soviet Union]], and the best-selling puzzle video game series.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[The Sims]]'' || [[2000 in video games|February 4, 2000]] || 200 million<ref name=\"2016 World Video Game Hall of Fame Inductees Announced\">{{cite web |url=http://www.museumofplay.org/press/releases/2016/05/2688-2016-world-video-game-hall-fame-inductees-announced/ |title=2016 World Video Game Hall of Fame Inductees Announced|website=museumofplay.org|date=May 5, 2016|accessdate=February 3, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | ''The Sims'' is a series of [[life simulation game]]s primarily for personal computers but later released for game consoles. It was created by American game designer [[Will Wright (game designer)|Will Wright]], developed by [[Maxis]] and published by [[Electronic Arts]]. The series consists of four main games and a number of compilations and expansion packs. It is currently the most successful PC game franchise of all time.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Minecraft]]'' || [[2011 in video games|November 18, 2011]] || 180 million<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dent |first1=Steve |title=Minecraft player count reaches 480 million |url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/minecraft/minecraft-player-count/ |website=[[PCGamesN]] |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''Minecraft'' is a [[sandbox video game|sandbox]]-building video game originally created by Swedish game designer [[Markus Persson|Markus \"Notch\" Persson]] and developed by [[Mojang]]. Originally a computer game made using [[Java (software platform)|Java]], it has since been ported to game consoles and mobile devices. It was bought by [[Microsoft Studios]] on September 15, 2014. It is the most successful video game franchise [[Sweden]] has produced, and is the single best-selling game of all time.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Need for Speed]]'' || [[1994 in video games|August 31, 1994]] || 150 million<ref name=\"needforspeed\">{{cite news | url=http://investor.ea.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=799755 | publisher=[[Electronic Arts]] | accessdate=2014-02-28 | date=2013-10-24 | title=EA Signs Multi-Year Agreement With X-Games Medalist and Internet Phenom Ken Block for Need for Speed}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''Need for Speed'' is a series of [[racing video game]]s published by [[Electronic Arts]], and has been developed by multiple companies over the years such as [[EA Black Box]] and [[Criterion Games]]. It is currently the most successful racing game franchise of all time.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Final Fantasy]]'' || [[1987 in video games|December 18, 1987]] || 149{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"2019_SE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/356047/SQUARE_ENIX_SPREADS_HOLIDAY_CHEER_WITH_MERRY_OFFERINGS_ON_FINAL_FANTASY_MOBILE_TITLES.php|title=SQUARE ENIX SPREADS HOLIDAY CHEER WITH MERRY OFFERINGS ON FINAL FANTASY MOBILE TITLES|website=[[Gamasutra]]|date=Dec 20, 2019|accessdate=Jan 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| {{nihongo foot|''[[Final Fantasy]]''|\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30ca\u30eb\u30d5\u30a1\u30f3\u30bf\u30b8\u30fc|Fainaru Fantaj\u012b|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[Japanese video game|Japanese]] [[science fantasy]] [[media franchise]], created by the Japanese video game designer [[Hironobu Sakaguchi]] and owned by [[Square Enix]]. The franchise encompasses fifteen signature [[role-playing video game]]s alongside a number of spin-off games, motion pictures, and many other consumer products and interactive media.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"background:#FFFFBF;\"| ''[[Mario Kart]]'' || [[1992 in video games|August 27, 1992]] || 145.14{{nbsp}}million{{#tag:ref|''Mario Kart'' series:\n* Up until March 2014 {{ndash}} 100.13{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"gi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2014/06/02/mario-kart-8-speeds-to-over-1-2-million-sales-in-opening-weekend.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140604084937/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2014/06/02/mario-kart-8-speeds-to-over-1-2-million-sales-in-opening-weekend.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 June 2014|title=Mario Kart 8 Speeds To Over 1.2 Million Sales In Opening Weekend|last=Futter|first=Mike|date=2 June 2014|work=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref>\n* ''Mario Kart 7'' sales from April 2014 to March 2019 {{ndash}} {{#expr:18.68-9.69}}{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"nintendo-software\"/><ref name=\"gi\"/>\n* ''[[Mario Kart 8]]'' (including ''[[Mario Kart 8 Deluxe]]'') sales from May 2014 to December 2019 {{ndash}} {{#expr:22.96+8.44}}{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"nintendo-software\"/>\n|group=n|name=MarioKart}}<ref name=\"gematsu.com\">{{Cite web | url = https://gematsu.com/2019/10/switch-worldwide-sales-top-41-67-million-he-legend-of-zelda-links-awakening-sales-top-3-13-million | title = Switch worldwide sales top 41.67 million, he Legend of Zelda: Link's Awakening sales top 3.13 million | first = Sal | last = Romano | date = October 31, 2019 | accessdate = October 31, 2019 | work = Gematsu }}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"|{{nihongo foot|''Mario Kart''|\u30de\u30ea\u30aa\u30ab\u30fc\u30c8|Mario K\u0101to}} is a series of [[kart racing game]]s developed and published by Nintendo. The series is a spin-off of the [[Mario (franchise)|''Mario'' franchise]] and has spawned eight main games, one enhanced game, four arcade games and a mobile game.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|''[[Assassin's Creed]]'' || [[2007 in video games|November 13, 2007]] || 140 million<ref name=\"ubisoft 2019\">{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamesn.com/assassins-creed-sales | title =Assassin's Creed all-time sales top 140 million | first = Ali | last = Jones | date = September 27, 2019 | accessdate= September 27, 2019 | work = [[PCGamesN]] }}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" |''Assassin's Creed'' is an [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[stealth game|stealth]] video game franchise developed by [[Ubisoft Montreal]] and published by [[Ubisoft]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Madden NFL]]'' || [[1988 in video games|June 1, 1988]] || 130 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investor.ea.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=1074764|title=Madden: Fans Are Going Mad for Madden, EA SPORTS Madden NFL Franchise Passes 130 Million Copies Sold|first=|last=|date=5 August 2018|publisher= Electronic Arts}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''[[Madden NFL]]'' is an [[American football]] video game series developed by Electronic Arts Tiburon for EA Sports. The series is named after [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]]r [[John Madden (American football)|John Madden]], a well-known [[color commentator]] for [[NBC Sports]] and formerly a [[Super Bowl]]-winning [[head coach]] during the 1970s with the [[Oakland Raiders]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"background:#FFFFBF;\"| ''[[Wii Sports]]'' || [[2006 in video games|November 19, 2006]] || 114.52 million<ref group=\"n\" name=\"Wii\"/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| The ''Wii Sports'' series of [[sports game]]s was created by Shigeru Miyamoto for the Nintendo Wii console in 2006. Its success led to the [[Wii (video game series)|''Wii'' video game series]], of which it is a sub-series. The first game in the series, ''Wii Sports'', was bundled with the original Wii console and is one the best-selling games of all time.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|''[[Pro Evolution Soccer]]'' || [[1995 in video games|July 21, 1995]] || 107.4 million<ref name=\"KHC\">{{cite web |title=Digital Entertainment Business |url=https://www.konami.com/corporate/en/business/digitalentertainment.html |website=Konami Holdings Corporation