]]|publisher=[[Berkshire Hathaway]]|date=December 3, 2001|accessdate=May 23, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020124210759/http://biz.yahoo.com/prnews/011203/sfm011_1.html|archivedate=January 24, 2002|via=[[Yahoo|Yahoo.com]]|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"|''Army Men'' is a series of video games developed by [[The 3DO Company|3DO]] and [[Global Star Software]] based around plastic army men.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Alone in the Dark]]'' || [[1992 in video gaming|1992]] || 6 million<ref name=\"infogrames20072008\">{{cite web | url=http://corporate.atari.com/MT-3.34-en/mt-static/FCKeditor/UserFiles/File/CA%20Q2%20FY07%2008%20FR%20%20FINAL_EUR(1).doc | format=[[Microsoft Word]] | date=2007-11-09 | accessdate=2008-01-06 | publisher=[[Infogrames]] | title=Consolidated revenue of 91.2 million euros for first half of fiscal 2007\u20132008 (unaudited preliminary results) }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''Alone in the Dark'' is a series of [[survival horror]] [[video game]]s from [[Infogrames]], based on the writings of [[H. P. Lovecraft]], although later games in the series drew inspiration from other sources, including [[Haitian Vodou|Voodoo]], the [[Wild West]], and the works of [[H.R. Giger]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Brothers in Arms (series)|Brothers in Arms]]'' || [[2005 in video gaming|March 1, 2005]] || 6 million<ref name=\"ubisoftgroup\"/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''Brothers in Arms'' is a [[first-person shooter]] [[video game]] series created by [[Gearbox Software]] and published by [[Ubisoft]], originally released in early 2005. The game takes place during [[World War II]] and focuses on team strategy rather than the faster paced run and gun tactics of the [[Medal of Honor series|''Medal of Honor'']] series.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Carmen Sandiego]]'' || [[1985 in video gaming|1985]] || 6 million<ref name=\"carmensandiego\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/3253/designers_notebook_games_for_.php | title=Girl Games: Adventures in Lip Gloss | date=1998-02-13 | accessdate=2008-01-09 | website=[[Gamasutra]] | author=Rebecca L. Eisenberg}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''Carmen Sandiego'' was originally conceived in 1983 by ex-[[Disney]] artist Gene Portwood, Mark Iscaro, Dane Bigham and [[Lauren Elliott]] at [[Br\u00f8derbund|Br\u00f8derbund Software]]. The concept for the product evolved from a game the Carlstons (founders of Br\u00f8derbund) played as kids, using the world almanac and maps to play quiz games. The franchise later developed into television series and books.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Championship Manager series|Championship Manager]]'' || [[1992 in video gaming|September 1, 1992]] || 6 million<ref name=\"scigames\">{{cite web | url=http://corporate.sci.co.uk/Who_we_are/brandportfolio.aspx | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080122112402/http://corporate.sci.co.uk/Who_we_are/brandportfolio.aspx | archivedate=2008-01-22 | title=Brand Portfolio | publisher=[[SCi Games|SCi]] | accessdate=2009-03-21}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| The ''Championship Manager'' series is a series of British [[Association football|football]]-management simulation. It was one of the most popular video game franchises of all time. The ''Championship Manager'' brand and game was conceived by two brothers: [[Collyer brothers (game designers)|Paul and Oliver Collyer]].  The series was split in two in 2005 as the Collyers decided that their vision of the game was at odds with that of publisher [[Eidos Interactive]] so they need to leave to continue making a game they could be proud of.  The brothers lost their battle to keep the ''Championship Manager'' name, however, and so their series was rebranded as ''[[Football Manager]]'' while Eidos continued to develop the game their own way under the ''Championship Manager'' moniker.<ref name=\"fmtrain\">{{cite web | url=http://footballmanagertraining.com/ | title=Football Manager Training | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100827181454/http://footballmanagertraining.com/ | archivedate=2010-08-27 }}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Hatsune Miku: Project DIVA]]'' || [[2009 in video gaming|July 2, 2009]] || 6{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"Sega2018\">[https://www.segasammy.co.jp/english/ir/library/pdf/printing_annual/2018/ssh_ar18e_web.pdf]</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''Hatsune Miku: Project DIVA''|\u521d\u97f3\u30df\u30af -Project DIVA-}} is a series of [[rhythm game]]s created by [[Sega]] and [[Crypton Future Media]] consisting of 6 main titles and 3 spin-offs, based primarily on the virtual-diva [[Vocaloid]] character [[Hatsune Miku]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[NBA Jam (series)|NBA Jam]]'' || [[1993 in video gaming|1993]] || 6 million<ref name=\"nbajam\">{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020602111122/http://www.acclaim.com/company/pressReleases/product/NBAJAM2004.html | url=http://www.acclaim.com/company/pressReleases/product/NBAJAM2004.html | archivedate=2002-06-02 | accessdate=2008-03-15 | publisher=[[Acclaim Entertainment]] | title=Acclaim Sports to Take Gamers to the Hole With 'NBA JAM 2004' for All Next-Generation Gaming Systems | date=2002-05-22}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''NBA Jam'' is a series of basketball-based video games created by [[Midway Games|Midway]] and later [[Electronic Arts]].\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Test Drive (series)|Test Drive]]''