t began in 1995 with the [[time travel]] [[role-playing video game]] ''[[Chrono Trigger]]'', which spawned two continuations, the [[visual novel]] ''[[Radical Dreamers]]'' and the role-playing game ''[[Chrono Cross]]''.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Drakengard]]'' || [[2003 in video gaming|September 11, 2003]] || 5.33 million{{efn|''Drakengard'' franchise:\n* ''Drakengard'' trilogy {{ndash}} 627,344 in Japan\n** ''[[Drakengard (video game)|Drakengard]]'' {{ndash}} 247,931<ref>{{cite web |title=Drakengard |url=http://salesdatabase.net/games/172/ |website=Japan Game Sales Database |accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n** ''[[Drakengard 2]]'' {{ndash}} 203,336<ref>{{cite web | title=GEIMIN.NET\uff0f2003\u5e74\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u58f2\u308a\u4e0a\u3052TOP300 | url=http://geimin.net/da/db/2003_ne_fa/index.php | work=Geimin.net | language=Japanese | accessdate=August 8, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228093934/http://geimin.net/da/db/2005_ne_fa/index.php|archivedate=December 28, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n** ''[[Drakengard 3]]'' {{ndash}} 176,077<ref>{{cite web |title=Drakengard 3 |url=http://salesdatabase.net/games/4211/ |website=Japan Game Sales Database |accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Nier'' sub-series {{ndash}} 4,700,000\n** ''[[Nier (video game)|Nier]]'' - 700,000 <ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20181031133013/http://www.hd.square-enix.com/jpn/ir/library/pdf/ar_2018_06feature.pdf SQUARE ENIX] June 2018</ref>\n** ''[[Nier: Automata]]'' {{ndash}} 4,000,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.siliconera.com/nier-automata-reaches-new-milestone-of-4-million-units-in-worldwide-shipments-and-digital-sales/|title=NieR: Automata Reaches New Milestone Of 4 Million Units In Worldwide Shipments And Digital Sales|date=May 13, 2019|work=Siliconera|access-date=November 26, 2019|language=en-US}}</ref>\n}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''Drakengard'' is a series of [[action role-playing video game]]s. It was conceived by Takamasa Shiba and Takuya Iwasaki as a gameplay hybrid between ''[[Ace Combat]]'' and ''[[Dynasty Warriors 2]]''. The story was created by Shiba, Iwasaki, [[Taro Yoko|Yoko Taro]] and Sawako Natori, who were influenced by European folklore and popular anime series and movies of the day. Shiba, Yoko, and Sawako have had involvement in every entry of the series since its debut. The setting of the main series is a [[Northern Europe]]an-style [[dark fantasy]] world where humans and creatures from myth and legends live side by side, while the spin-off game is set in an alternative reality leading from one of the first game's possible endings. The world has been described by ''[[Anime News Network]]'' as \"a warped version of medieval Europe\".\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[Anno 1602|Anno]]'' || [[1998 in video gaming|September 24, 1998]] || 5 million<ref name=\"ubisoftgroup\" /><ref name=\"anno\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/News/Story/200704/N07.0411.1346.21289.htm |archive-url=https://archive.today/20070528113350/http://www.gameinformer.com/News/Story/200704/N07.0411.1346.21289.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-05-28 |magazine=[[Game Informer]] |date=2007-04-11 |author=Billy Berghammer |accessdate=2008-01-08 |title=Ubisoft Acquires RTS Developer SunFlowers }}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"| ''Anno'' is a series of games with both [[real time strategy]] and [[city-building game|city building]] elements, developed by Germany-based [[Sunflowers Interactive Entertainment Software]] company.\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#e6e9ff; height:3px;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| ''[[List of Asterix games|Asterix]]'' || [[1983 in video gaming|1983]] || 5 million<ref name=\"asterix\">{{cite press release | url=http://corporate.atari.com/infogramesgb/2003/06/atari_to_announce_asterix_xxl.php | publisher=[[